\begin_layout Section
Topological Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
topological space 
\series default
is an ordered pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\tau)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a nonempty set and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is a collection of subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, satisfying the following axioms:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The empty set 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and the enitre set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is closed under arbitrary unions: if 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\in\tau$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in some arbitrary index set 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i\in I}U_{i}\in\tau$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is closed under finite intersections: if 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1},\dots,U_{n}\in\tau$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcap_{m=1}^{n}U_{m}\in\tau$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
open sets 
\series default
and the collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
topology 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We often just write 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\tau)$
\end_inset

 to denote a topological space.
 We also say 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 a topology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Typically, one describes a topological space by specifying its open sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Comparison of Topologies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau'$
\end_inset

 be two topologies on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\subseteq\tau'$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
coarser 
\series default
(
\series bold
weaker 
\series default
or 
\series bold
smaller
\series default
) topology than 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\subseteq\tau'$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau'$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
finer 
\series default
(
\series bold
stronger 
\series default
or 
\series bold
larger
\series default
) 
\series bold
topology 
\series default
than 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau'$
\end_inset

 be two topologies on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

-open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau'$
\end_inset

-open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}'$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}'\subseteq U_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau'$
\end_inset

 is finer than 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\in\tau$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, choose a 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau'$
\end_inset

-open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}'$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}'\subseteq U$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
U & =\bigcup_{x\in U}U_{x}'\\
 & \in\tau'.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau'$
\end_inset

 is finer than 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Subspace Topology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\tau)$
\end_inset

 be a topological space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We can give 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 a topology by declaring open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 to be all sets of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap Z$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 One easily verifies that the collection of these open sets satisfy the
 axioms of forming a topology.
 We call this the 
\series bold
subspace topology induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Generating a Topology from a Collection of Subsets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty collection of subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a smallest topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}$
\end_inset

.
 It is called the 
\series bold
topology generated by 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}$
\end_inset

 and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(\mathscr{C})$
\end_inset

.
 We also call 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
subbase 
\series default
for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(\mathscr{C})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(\mathscr{C})$
\end_inset

 to be the collection of all subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 obtained by adjoining to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}$
\end_inset

 the set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 itself, empty set, and all arbitary unions of finite intersections of members
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}$
\end_inset

.
 To see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(\mathscr{C})$
\end_inset

 is a topology, note that arbitrary unions of arbitrary unions of finite
 intersections is an arbitrary union of finite intersections, so it suffices
 to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(\mathscr{C})$
\end_inset

 is closed under finite intersections.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A,A'\in\tau(\mathscr{C})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\bigcup_{i\in I}(C_{i,1}\cap C_{i,2}\cap\cdots\cap C_{i,n_{i}})
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i,j}\in\mathscr{C}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j\leq n_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A'=\bigcup_{i'\in I'}(C_{i',1}'\cap C_{i',2}'\cap\cdots\cap C_{i',n_{i'}'}')
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i',j'}'\in\mathscr{C}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i'}'\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i'\in I'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j'\leq n_{i'}'$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
A\cap A' & =A\cap\left(\bigcup_{i'\in I'}(C_{i',1}'\cap C_{i',2}'\cap\cdots\cap C_{i',n_{i'}'}')\right)\\
 & =\bigcup_{i'\in I'}\left(A\cap C_{i',1}'\cap C_{i',2}'\cap\cdots\cap C_{i',n_{i'}'}'\right)\\
 & =\bigcup_{i'\in I'}\left(\left(\bigcup_{i\in I}(C_{i,1}\cap C_{i,2}\cap\cdots\cap C_{i,n_{i}})\right)\cap C_{i',1}'\cap C_{i',2}'\cap\cdots\cap C_{i',n_{i'}'}'\right)\\
 & =\bigcup_{i'\in I'}\left(\bigcup_{i\in I}(C_{i,1}\cap C_{i,2}\cap\cdots\cap C_{i,n_{i}}\cap C_{i',1}'\cap C_{i',2}'\cap\cdots\cap C_{i',n_{i'}'}')\right)\\
 & =\bigcup_{(i,i')\in I\times I'}(C_{i,1}\cap C_{i,2}\cap\cdots\cap C_{i,n_{i}}\cap C_{i',1}'\cap C_{i',2}'\cap\cdots\cap C_{i',n_{i'}'}')\\
 & \in\tau(\mathscr{C}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(\mathscr{C})$
\end_inset

 is closed under finite intersections.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\tau)$
\end_inset

 be a topological space.
 A collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{B}$
\end_inset

 of open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
base 
\series default
(or 
\series bold
basis
\series default
)
\series bold
 
\series default
for
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 
\series default
if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{B}$
\end_inset

 covers 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $U,V\in\mathscr{B}$
\end_inset

 and for all points 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U\cap V$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $W\in\mathscr{B}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in W\subseteq U\cap V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Neighborhoods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 An open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is called an 
\series bold
open neighborhood of
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a basis element in the topology, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
basic open neighborhood
\series default
 
\series bold
of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Continuous Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be topological spaces.
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
continuous 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
continous at a point
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 if for any open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U)\subseteq V$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To check continuity of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, it is enough to shows that for any 
\emph on
basic
\emph default
 open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U)\subseteq V_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if this property holds, then for any open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, we choose a basic open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 and an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U)\subseteq V_{0}\subseteq V$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be topological spaces.
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is continous if and only if it is continuous at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continous.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continous and, moreover, it contains 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 is an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 was arbitary, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continous at every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continous at every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 We need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in f^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

, we can find an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}\subset f^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U_{x})\subseteq V$
\end_inset

), since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continous at every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}(V)=\bigcup_{x\in f^{-1}(V)}U_{x}
\]

\end_inset

implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 is open.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is continuous at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in X$
\end_inset

.
 One may suspect that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous in some open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

, but this is not the case.
 For a counterexample, consider the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\begin{cases}
x^{2} & \text{if }x\text{ is rational},\\
0 & \text{if }x\text{ is irrational}.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 but is not continuous anywhere else.
 To show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\varepsilon}(0)$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

-ball centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $f(0)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(B_{\sqrt{\varepsilon}}(0)\right)\subset B_{\varepsilon}(0)$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B_{\sqrt{\varepsilon}}(0)$
\end_inset

 is rational, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=0\in B_{\varepsilon}(0)$
\end_inset

 and if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B_{\sqrt{\varepsilon}}(0)$
\end_inset

 is irrational, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{2}\in B_{\varepsilon}(0)$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|<\sqrt{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

).
 It is an easy exercise to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is not continuous anywhere else.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X,Y$
\end_inset

 be topological spaces, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a continuous function, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset X$
\end_inset

 be given the subspace topology.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{A}\colon A\to Y$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $(f|_{A})^{-1}(V)=f^{-1}(V)\cap A$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Continuity in Metric Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
metric 
\series default
on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $d:X\times X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 which satisfies the following three properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Identity of indiscernibles) 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,y)=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Symmetric) 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,y)=d(y,x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Triangle Inequality) 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,z)\leq d(x,y)+d(y,z)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z\in X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 together with a choice of a metric 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
metric space 
\series default
and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

, or just denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 if the metric is understood from context.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Given the three axioms above, we also have 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,y)\geq0$
\end_inset

 (positive-definitene) for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =d(x,x)\\
 & \leq d(x,y)+d(y,x)\\
 & =d(x,y)+d(x,y)\\
 & =2d(x,y).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,y)\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Open Balls
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 be a metric space.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

, we define the 
\series bold
open ball centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset


\series default
, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\varepsilon}(x)$
\end_inset

, to be the set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{\varepsilon}(x):=\left\{ y\in X\mid d(x,y)<\varepsilon\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 be a metric space.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\varepsilon}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\varepsilon'}(x')$
\end_inset

 are two open balls centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 (resp.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x'\in X$
\end_inset

) of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 (resp.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon'>0$
\end_inset

) such that 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\varepsilon}(x)\cap B_{\varepsilon'}(x')\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x''\in X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon''>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{\varepsilon''}(x'')\subseteq B_{\varepsilon}(x)\cap B_{\varepsilon'}(x).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Pick any 
\begin_inset Formula $x''\in B_{\varepsilon}(x)\cap B_{\varepsilon'}(x')$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=d(x,x'')$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta'=d(x',x'')$
\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon-\delta\leq\varepsilon'-\delta'$
\end_inset

.
 Then we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon''=\varepsilon-\delta$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in B_{\varepsilon''}(x)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d(x,y) & \leq d(x,x'')+d(x'',y)\\
 & =\delta+d(x'',y)\\
 & <\varepsilon
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in B_{\varepsilon}(x)$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d(x',y) & \leq d(x',x'')+d(x'',y)\\
 & =\delta'+d(x'',y)\\
 & <\delta'+\varepsilon-\delta\\
 & \leq\varepsilon'
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in B_{\varepsilon'}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 be a metric space.
 The proposition above implies that the open balls form the base for a topology
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, making it a topological space.
 A topological space which can arise in this way from a metric space is
 called a 
\series bold
metrizable 
\series default
space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Epsilon-Delta and Metric Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is continuous at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

 if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|q-p\|<\delta\text{ implies }\|f(q)-f(p)\|<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset

In terms of open sets, this says for all basic open neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\varepsilon}(f(p))$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)$
\end_inset

, there is a basic open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\delta}(p)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(B_{\delta}(p))\subseteq B_{\varepsilon}(f(p))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(Y,d)$
\end_inset

 be metric spaces.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is continous at at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 if and only if for all sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{n})\to f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continous at 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

.
 We need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{n})\to f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $x,$
\end_inset

 there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U)\subseteq V$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\in U$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{n})\in V$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{n})\to f(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose that for all sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{n})\to f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 We need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 We will prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 by contradiction: assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is not continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Choose an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 such that there is no neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U)\subseteq V$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{n}:=B_{\frac{1}{n}}(x):=\left\{ x'\in X\mid d(x,x')<\frac{1}{n}\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}'\in U_{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{n}')\notin V$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n}')$
\end_inset

 is a sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}'\to x$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{n}')\not\to f(x)$
\end_inset

 (indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{n}')$
\end_inset

 is never in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

).
 Contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the step function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\begin{cases}
0 & \text{if }x\leq0\\
1 & \text{if }x>0.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is not continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 since, for example, the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/n)\to0$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $(f(1/n))\to1\ne f(0)$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1/n)\to0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(-1/n)=0=f(0)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we really do need 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to preserve 
\emph on
all 
\emph default
convergent sequences in order for it to be continuous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
First-Countable Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
first-countable 
\series default
if each point has a countable neighborhood basis.
 That is, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, there exists a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{n})$
\end_inset

 of open neighborhoods of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that for any open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{n}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a continuous function and assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is first-countable.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continous at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 if and only if for all sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{n})\to f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continous at 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

.
 Choose an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $x,$
\end_inset

 we can choose an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U)\subseteq V$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

, there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(x_{n}) & \in f(U)\\
 & \subseteq V.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{n})\to f(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose that for all sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{n})\to f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is not continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Choose an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 such that there does not exist an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U)\subseteq V$
\end_inset

.
 Now we apply first-countability of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a neighborhood basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\in U_{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{n})\notin V$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

 since for any open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, we can find an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{n}\in U_{N}\subseteq U.
\]

\end_inset

On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{n})\not\to f(x)$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{n})\notin V$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Discrete Topologies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a set.
 The 
\series bold
discrete topology 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is defined by letting every subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be open.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be topological spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 has the discrete topology.
 Then every continous map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is locally constant
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This means for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is constant on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $f(y)=f(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in U_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has the discrete topology, then every function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is continous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a continous function and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f(x)\}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 has the discrete topology.
 Denote 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 to be the inverse image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f(x)\}$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{x}:=f^{-1}\{f(x)\}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 is an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 on which 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is constant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a function and let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is discrete, every subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is open.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 is open.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Weakest Topology on Codomain 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a set, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{X_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be a collection of topological spaces, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{i}:X_{i}\to X\}$
\end_inset

 be a collection of functions.
 We want to give 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 a topology such that the maps 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 become continuous.
 We do this by declaring a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to be open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}^{-1}(U)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 That this really is a topology follows from the identities:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{i}^{-1}\left(\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}U_{\lambda}\right)=\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}f_{i}^{-1}(U_{\lambda})\text{ and }f_{i}^{-1}\left(\bigcap_{\lambda\in\Lambda}U_{\lambda}\right)=\bigcap_{\lambda\in\Lambda}f_{i}^{-1}(U_{\lambda}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Weakest Topology on Domain 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a set, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{X_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be a collection of topological spaces, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{i}:X\to X_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 be a collection of functions.
 We want to give 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 a topology such that the maps 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 become continuous.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

, then certainly we need 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}^{-1}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 to be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We give 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 the smallest topology that contains all sets of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}^{-1}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gluing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space.
 An 
\series bold
open covering 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigcup_{i\in I}U_{i}=X.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{X_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 be an open covering, so each 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 gets an induced topology.
 Note that a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap X_{i}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, one direction is clear.
 For the other direction, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap X_{i}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, there exists an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cap X_{i}=U\cap X$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\bigcup_{i\in I}U\cap X_{i}=\bigcup_{i\in I}U_{i}\cap X_{i},
\]

\end_inset

shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a union of open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is a continouous map, then by restriction to 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 we get continuous maps 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}:X_{i}\to Y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{i}\mid_{X_{i}\cap X_{j}}=f_{j}\mid_{X_{i}\cap X_{j}}\text{ for all }i\text{ and }j\label{eq:continuoussheaf}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Conversely, if we are given continuous maps 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}:X_{i}\to Y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:continuoussheaf})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 holds, then there is a unique set-theoretic map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mid_{X_{i}}=f_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, and moreover it is continuous.
 Indeed, for any open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(V)\cap X_{i}=f_{i}^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, we can view continuous maps 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to Y$
\end_inset

 as collections of continuous maps 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}\to Y$
\end_inset

 that are compatible on the overlaps 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}\cap X_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 We want to run this procedure in reverse.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a set, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{X_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 be a collection of subsets whose union is 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose on each 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 there is a given topology 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

 and that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

's are compatible in the following sense: 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}\cap X_{j}$
\end_inset

 is open in each of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j}$
\end_inset

, and the induced topologies on 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}\cap X_{j}$
\end_inset

 from both 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j}$
\end_inset

 coincide.
 There is a unique topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that induces upon each 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 the topology 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We say that the topology in this theorem is obtained by 
\series bold
gluing 
\series default
the given topologies on the 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

's (We may also say that the topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\tau)$
\end_inset

 is obtained by 
\series bold
gluing 
\series default
the topological spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $(X_{i},\tau_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first prove uniqueness.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is a topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 inducing 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and making 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, then a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is open for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap X_{i}$
\end_inset

 is open for the induced topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 (as 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

-open for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

), and hence (by the assumption that the induced topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

) if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap X_{i}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

-open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 This final formulation of the openness condition for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is expressed entirely in terms of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

's and so establishes uniqueness: we have no choice as to what the condition
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

-openness is to be, and it must be the case that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

-open sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are exactly those that meet each 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 in a 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

-open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We now run the process in reverse to verify the existence.
 We 
\emph on
define 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 to be the collection of subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap X_{i}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

-open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 This topology is the weakest topology which makes the inclusion maps 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}\hookrightarrow X$
\end_inset

 continuous.
 Since for each fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{0}$
\end_inset

 the overlap 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i_{0}}\cap X_{j}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}$
\end_inset

-open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

-open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Compactness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
compact 
\series default
every open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 contains a finite subcovering of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

: if 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 covers 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i_{1}},U_{i_{2}},\dots,U_{i_{n}}\in\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i_{k}}\}_{k=1}^{n}$
\end_inset

 covers 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We say a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
compact subset
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is compact with respect to the subspace topology.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 be a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 To check for compactness for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, it is enough to only consider open coverings 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 are in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 be a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is compact if and only if every open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 consisting of basis elements contains a finite subcovering of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 One direction is clear.
 For the other direction, assume that every open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 consisting of basis elements contains a finite subcovering of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (where the 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 are not necessarily basis elements).
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{V_{i,j}\}_{j\in J}$
\end_inset

 be an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 consisting of basis elements (so the 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 are basis elements).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{V_{i,j}\}_{i\in I,j\in J}$
\end_inset

 is an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 consisting of basis elements and so there exists a finite subcovering,
 say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{V_{i_{\lambda},j_{\gamma}}\}_{\lambda\in\Lambda,\gamma\in\Gamma}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 are finite sets.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i_{\lambda}}\}_{\lambda\in\Lambda}$
\end_inset

 is a finite subcovering of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The proposition above is still true if we replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 with a subbase.
 However to prove this, we would need to use the Ultrafilter principle.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmacompactsubspaceofhausdorffspaceisclosed}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be Hausdorff and let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a compact subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We show that 
\begin_inset Formula $X\backslash K$
\end_inset

 is open.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X\backslash K$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in K$
\end_inset

, choose an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{y}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{y}\cap V_{y}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is compact, the open covering 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{y}\cap K\}_{y\in K}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 contains a finite subcovering of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{y_{i}}\cap K\}_{i=1}^{n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\in K$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{x}:=\bigcap_{i=1}^{n}V_{y_{i}}
\]

\end_inset

is an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 which does not meet 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\backslash K=\bigcup_{x\in X\backslash K}V_{x},
\]

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $X\backslash K$
\end_inset

 is open, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Image of a Compact Space is Compact
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a continuous function from a compact space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is a compact subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{V_{j}\cap f(X)\}_{j\in J}$
\end_inset

 be an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

, where the 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{j}$
\end_inset

 are open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f^{-1}(V_{j})\}_{j\in J}$
\end_inset

 is an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is compact, there exists a finite subcover of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f^{-1}(V_{j})\}_{j\in J}$
\end_inset

 wich covers 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f^{-1}(V_{j_{1}}),\dots,f^{-1}(V_{j_{k}})\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{V_{j_{1}}\cap f(X),\dots,V_{j_{k}}\cap f(X)\}$
\end_inset

 is a finite subcover of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{V_{j}\cap f(X)\}_{j\in J}$
\end_inset

 which covers 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Finite Intersection Property
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is another way of thinking about compactness.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 satisfies the 
\series bold
finite intersection property 
\series default
(or 
\series bold
FIP
\series default
) for closed sets if any collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\{Z_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of closed sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with all finite intersections 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z_{i_{1}}\cap\cdots\cap Z_{i_{n}}\neq\emptyset,
\]

\end_inset

the intersection 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcap_{i\in I}Z_{i}$
\end_inset

 of all 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{i}$
\end_inset

's is non-empty.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is compact if and only if it satisfies FIP for closed sets.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This is an exercise in linguistics.
 Suppose first that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 To obtain a contradiction, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 does not satisfy FIP for closed sets.
 Then there exists a collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\{Z_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of closed sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with all finite intersections 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{i_{1}}\cap\cdots\cap Z_{i_{n}}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcap_{i\in I}Z_{i}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 But this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\{X\backslash Z_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with no finite subcover.
 The converse is proved in exactly the same way.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
When a continuous bijection is a homeomorphism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmaclosedsubpaceofcompactspaceiscompact}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a compact space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be a closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is also compact.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\cap E\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(X\backslash E)\cup\{U_{i}\cap E\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is compact, there exists a finite subcover in 
\begin_inset Formula $(X\backslash E)\cup\{U_{i}\cap E\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this implies that there exists a finite subcover in 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\cap E\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmaimageofcompactiscompact}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a compact space, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be any topological space, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be continuous surjective map.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{V_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f^{-1}(V_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is compact, there exists a finite subcover in 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f^{-1}(V_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f^{-1}(V_{i_{1}}),\dots,f^{-1}(V_{i_{n}})\}$
\end_inset

.
 But then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{V_{i_{1}},\dots,V_{i_{n}}\}$
\end_inset

 is a finite subcover in 
\begin_inset Formula $\{V_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremcompacttohausdorffcontinuousbijection}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be topological spaces such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is compact and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a continuous bijection.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g:Y\to X$
\end_inset

 denote the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 We need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 We do this by showing that the inverse image of a closed set in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a closed set in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be a closed set in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is compact, 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is compact by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaclosedsubpaceofcompactspaceiscompact})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is compact, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(E)$
\end_inset

 is compact by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaimageofcompactiscompact})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(E)$
\end_inset

 is compact, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(E)$
\end_inset

 is closed by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmacompactsubspaceofhausdorffspaceisclosed})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $f(V)=g^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Closes subspaces of compact spaces are compact
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a compact space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a closed subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\cap A\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(X\backslash A)\cup\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is compact, it contains a finite subcovering of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $(X\backslash A)\cup\{U_{i_{k}}\}_{k=1}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 But then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i_{k}}\cap A\}_{k=1}^{n}$
\end_inset

 must be a finite subcovering of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\cap A\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Heine-Borel Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a subset of a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
limit point 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 if every open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 meets 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

: if 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap S\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a subset of Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is compact if and only if it is closed and bounded.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmacompactsubspaceofhausdorffspaceisclosed})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 It remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is bounded, which we will do by contradiction: assume 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is not bounded.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}=B_{1}(x)$
\end_inset

 be the open ball of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{x}\}_{x\in S}$
\end_inset

 forms an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is compact, there eixsts a finite subcover of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{x}\}_{x\in S}$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{x_{1}},\dots,U_{x_{n}}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{ij}=\sup\left\{ \|a_{i}-a_{j}\|\mid a_{i}\in U_{x_{i}}\text{ and }a_{j}\in U_{x_{j}}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is finite since 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{ij}\leq\|x_{i}-x_{j}\|+2$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\max_{1\leq i,j\leq n}\{L_{ij}\}$
\end_inset

, we see that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,a'\in S$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\|a-a'\|\leq L$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is bounded.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is closed and bounded.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is bounded, it is enclosed within an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-box 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}=[-a,a]^{n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff, a closed subset of a compact set is compact, and so it suffices
 to show 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 Assume, by way of contradiction, that 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset

 is not compact.
 Then there exists an infinite open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset

 that does not admit any finite subcover.
 Through bisection of each of the sides of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset

, the box 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset

 can be broken up into 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{n}$
\end_inset

 sub 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-boxes, each of which has diameter equal to half the diameter of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then at least one of the 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{n}$
\end_inset

 sections of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset

 must require an infinite subcover of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

, otherwise 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 itself would have a finite subcover, by uniting together the finite covers
 of the sections.
 Call this section 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Likewise, the sides of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

 can be bisected, yielded 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{n}$
\end_inset

 sections of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

, at least one of which must require an infinite subcover of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Continuing in this manner yields a decreasing sequence of nexted 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-boxes: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{0}\supset T_{1}\supset T_{2}\supset\cdots\supset T_{k}\supset\cdots
\]

\end_inset

where the side length of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $(2a)/2^{k}$
\end_inset

, which tends to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 tends to infinity.
 Let us define a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{k})$
\end_inset

 such that each 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{k}$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 This sequence is Cauchy, so it must converge to some limit 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Since each 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}$
\end_inset

 is closed, and for each 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{k})$
\end_inset

 is eventually always inside 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in T_{k}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 covers 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset

, it has some member 
\begin_inset Formula $U\in\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is open, there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-ball 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\varepsilon}(x)\subset U$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 For large enough 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 (for example such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(2a)/2^{k}<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

), one has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{k}\subset B_{\varepsilon}(x)\subset U,
\]

\end_inset

but then the infinite number of members of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 needed to cover 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}$
\end_inset

 can be replaced by just one: 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, a contradiction.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The Heine-Borel theorem does not hold as stated for general metric and
 topological vector spaces.
 For instance, at one point in our proof we used completeness, which doesn't
 hold in a general metric space.
 A metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 is said to have the 
\series bold
Heine-Borel property 
\series default
if each closed bounded set in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sequential Compactness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
sequentially compact 
\series default
if every sequence of points in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has a convergent subsequence converging to a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 In general, there are compact spaces which are not sequentially compact
 and there are sequentially compact spaces that are not compact.
 However, when it comes to metric spaces, these notions are equivalent.
 We will prove this in the case of the Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a subset of Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is sequentially compact if and only if it is closed and bounded.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is sequentially compact.
 We will first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is closed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a convergent sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, and suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is sequentially compact, we can choose a convergent subsequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n_{k}})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 which converges to a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Since every convergent subsequence of a convergent sequence converges to
 the same limit, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n_{k}}\to x$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $k\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 This establishes that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is closed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is bounded.
 Assume (for a contradiction) that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is unbounded.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is unbounded, there exists a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{n}\notin\bigcup_{m=1}^{n-1}B_{1}(x_{m}).
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Such a sequence has no convergent subsequence since for each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, the neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 contains only one member in the sequence (namely 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To complete the proof of the theorem, we now assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is closed and bounded.
 We will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is sequentially compact.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is closed and bounded, it lies in a closed box, say 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}=[-a,a]^{n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

.
 Through bisection of each of the sides of 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}$
\end_inset

, the box 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}$
\end_inset

 can be broken up into 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{n}$
\end_inset

 sub 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-boxes, each of which has diameter equal to half the diameter of 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then at least one of the 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{n}$
\end_inset

 sections of 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}$
\end_inset

 contains infinitely elements in the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Call this section 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Likewise, the sides of 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 can be bisected, yielded 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{n}$
\end_inset

 sections of 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

, at least one of which must contain infinitely many elements in the sequence
 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Continuing in this manner yields a decreasing sequence of nexted 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-boxes: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{0}\supset B_{1}\supset B_{2}\supset\cdots\supset B_{k}\supset\cdots
\]

\end_inset

where the side length of 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{k}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $(2a)/2^{k}$
\end_inset

, which tends to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 tends to infinity.
 Now we define a convergent subsequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 as follows: For each 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, we choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n_{k}}$
\end_inset

 inductively on 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 to be a member of the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 which lies in the box 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{k}$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n_{k}}\neq x_{n_{k-1}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 The sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n_{k}})$
\end_inset

 is is Cauchy, so it must converge to some limit 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Since each 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}$
\end_inset

 is closed, and for each 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{k})$
\end_inset

 is eventually always inside 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in T_{k}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, since 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is closed, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S$
\end_inset

.
 This establishes that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is sequentially compact.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Extreme Value Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a compact space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be continuous.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 obtains a maximum value, i.e.
 there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{0})\geq f(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is nonempty, otherwise it is trivial.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is compact, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is a compact subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 By the Heine-Borel theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is a closed and bounded subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is nonempty and bounded above, the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup(f(X))$
\end_inset

 exists.
 Moreover, since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is closed and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup f(X)$
\end_inset

 is a limit point of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup(f(X))\in f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup(f(X))=f(x_{0})$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in X$
\end_inset

, and this is clearly the maximum value.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Closure and Interior
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Closure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
closure 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A}$
\end_inset

, is the smallest closed set in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 It is characterized by the universal property that if 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is a closed set in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subseteq A$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subseteq\overline{A}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{A}=\bigcap_{\substack{E\text{ closed}\\
A\subseteq E
}
}E.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Uniqueness of Continuous Extensions of Functions from a Set to its Closure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmaopenneighborhoodmeets}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\overline{A}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 meets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap A\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To obtain a contradiction, assume 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap A=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is contained in the closed set 
\begin_inset Formula $X/U$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A}$
\end_inset

 is contained in the closed set 
\begin_inset Formula $X\backslash U$
\end_inset

.
 But this is a contradiction since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\overline{A}\cap U$
\end_inset

, whence 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\overline{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin X\backslash U$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propuniquenessofextensions}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be topological spaces such that 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon A\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a continuous map.
 Suppose there exists a continuous extension 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}\colon\overline{A}\to Y$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}(a)=f(a)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

), then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is unique.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To prove uniqueness, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}_{1}\colon\overline{A}\to Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}_{2}\colon\overline{A}\to Y$
\end_inset

 are two continuous extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\overline{A}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}_{1}(x)\neq\widetilde{f}_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Choose open neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{2}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}_{1}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

 respectively such that 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}\cap V_{2}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 (we can do this since 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}_{1}^{-1}(V_{1})\cap\widetilde{f}_{2}^{-1}(V_{2})$
\end_inset

 is an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\overline{A}$
\end_inset

, and so it must meet 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaopenneighborhoodmeets})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction though, since 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A\cap\widetilde{f}_{1}^{-1}(V_{1})\cap f_{2}^{-1}(V_{2})$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}\cap V_{2}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
V_{1} & \ni\widetilde{f}_{1}(a)\\
 & =f_{1}(a)\\
 & =f_{2}(a)\\
 & =\widetilde{f}_{2}(a)\in V_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propuniquenessofextensions}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological spaces such that 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff.
 Suppose that for every subset 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon A\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a continuous map.
 Suppose there exists a continuous extension 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}\colon\overline{A}\to Y$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}(a)=f(a)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

), then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is unique.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To prove uniqueness, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}_{1}\colon\overline{A}\to Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}_{2}\colon\overline{A}\to Y$
\end_inset

 are two continuous extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\overline{A}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}_{1}(x)\neq\widetilde{f}_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Choose open neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{2}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}_{1}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

 respectively such that 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}\cap V_{2}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 (we can do this since 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}_{1}^{-1}(V_{1})\cap\widetilde{f}_{2}^{-1}(V_{2})$
\end_inset

 is an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\overline{A}$
\end_inset

, and so it must meet 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaopenneighborhoodmeets})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction though, since 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A\cap\widetilde{f}_{1}^{-1}(V_{1})\cap f_{2}^{-1}(V_{2})$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}\cap V_{2}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
V_{1} & \ni\widetilde{f}_{1}(a)\\
 & =f_{1}(a)\\
 & =f_{2}(a)\\
 & =\widetilde{f}_{2}(a)\in V_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Metric Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
metric 
\series default
on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $d\colon X\times X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 which satisfies the following three properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Identity of Indiscernibles) 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,y)=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Symmetric) 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,y)=d(y,x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Triangle Inequality) 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,z)\leq d(x,y)+d(y,z)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z\in X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 together with a choice of a metric 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
metric space 
\series default
and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

, or just denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 if the metric is understood from context.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Given the three axioms above, we also have 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,y)\geq0$
\end_inset

 (Positive-Definiteness) for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =d(x,x)\\
 & \leq d(x,y)+d(y,x)\\
 & =d(x,y)+d(x,y)\\
 & =2d(x,y).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,y)\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 On 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
Euclidean metric 
\series default
is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{E}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=\|\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{y}\|=\sqrt{(x_{1}-y_{1})^{2}+\cdots+(x_{m}-y_{m})^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

This is the usual distance used in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, and when we speak about 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 as a metric space without specifying a metric, it's the Euclidean metric
 that is intended.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To check that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{E}$
\end_inset

 is a metric on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, the first two conditions in the definition are obvious.
 The third condition is a consequence of the inequality 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{y}\|\le\|\mathbf{x}\|+\|\mathbf{y}\|$
\end_inset

 (replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{z}-\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

), and to show this inequality holds we will write 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\mathbf{x}\|$
\end_inset

 in terms of the dot product: 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\mathbf{x}\|^{2}=x_{1}^{2}+\cdots+x_{m}^{2}=\mathbf{x}\cdot\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, so 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{y}\|^{2} & =(\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{y})\cdot(\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{y})\\
 & =\mathbf{x}\cdot\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{x}\cdot\mathbf{y}+\mathbf{y}\cdot\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{y}\cdot\mathbf{y}\\
 & =\|\mathbf{x}\|^{2}+2\mathbf{x}\cdot\mathbf{y}+\|\mathbf{y}\|^{2}\\
 & \leq\|\mathbf{x}\|^{2}+2|\mathbf{x}\cdot\mathbf{y}|+\|\mathbf{y}\|^{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The famous Cauchy-Schwarz inequality says 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mathbf{x}\cdot\mathbf{y}|\leq\|\mathbf{x}\|\|\mathbf{y}\|$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{y}\|^{2}\leq\|\mathbf{x}\|^{2}+2\|\mathbf{x}\|\|\mathbf{y}\|+\|\mathbf{y}\|^{2}=(\|\mathbf{x}\|+\|\mathbf{y}\|)^{2}
\]

\end_inset

and now take square roots.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A different metric on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{\infty}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=\max_{1\leq i\leq m}|x_{i}-y_{i}|.
\]

\end_inset

Again, the first two conditions of being a metric are clear, and to check
 the triangle inequality we use the fact that it is known for the absolute
 value.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\max|x_{i}-y_{i}|=|x_{k}-y_{k}|$
\end_inset

 for a particular 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 from
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=|x_{k}-y_{k}|$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d_{\infty}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}) & \leq|x_{k}-z_{k}|+|z_{k}-y_{k}|\\
 & \leq\max_{1\leq i\leq m}|x_{i}-z_{i}|+\max_{1\leq i\leq m}|z_{i}-y_{i}|\\
 & =d_{\infty}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})+d_{\infty}(\mathbf{z},\mathbf{y}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

While the metrics 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{E}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 are different, they're not that different from each other since each is
 bounded by a constant multiple of the other one: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{E}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\leq\sqrt{m}d_{\infty}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\text{ and }d_{\infty}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\leq d_{E}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{examplecontinuous01}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C[0,1]$
\end_inset

 be the space of all continuous functions from 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Two metrics used on 
\begin_inset Formula $C[0,1]$
\end_inset

 are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{\infty}(f,g)=\max_{0\leq x\leq1}|f(x)-g(x)|\text{ and }d_{1}(f,g)=\int_{0}^{1}|f(x)-g(x)|dx.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike with the two metrics on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 while we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}(f,g)\leq d_{\infty}(f,g)$
\end_inset

 there is no constant 
\begin_inset Formula $A>0$
\end_inset

 that makes 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}(f,g)\leq Ad_{1}(f,g)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 These metrics 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $C[0,1]$
\end_inset

 are quite different.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Metric Space Induced by a Norm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be a vector space over a subfield 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 of the complex numbers.
 A 
\series bold
norm 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a nonnegative-valued scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $p:V\to[0,\infty)$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in V$
\end_inset

, we have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Subadditivity) 
\begin_inset Formula $p(u+v)\leq p(u)+p(v)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Absolutely Homogeneous) 
\begin_inset Formula $p(av)=|a|p(v)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Positive-Definite) 
\begin_inset Formula $p(v)=0$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $v=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We call the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,p)$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
normed vector space
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,p)$
\end_inset

 be a normed vector space.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $d:V\times V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $d(u,v)=p(u-v)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,v)\in V\times V$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,d)$
\end_inset

 is a metric space.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let us first check that 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 satisfies the identity of indiscernibles property.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is positive-definite, 
\begin_inset Formula $d(u,v)=0$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p(u-v)=0$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $u=v$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $u=v$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is absolutely homogeneous, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p(0)=|0|p(0)=0$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $d(u,u)=p(0)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we check that 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is symmetric.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,v)\in V\times V$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d(u,v) & =p(u-v)\\
 & =p(-1(v-u))\\
 & =|-1|p(v-u)\\
 & =p(v-u)\\
 & =d(v,u).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finally, triangle inequality for 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 follows from subadditivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v,w\in V$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d(u,v)+d(v,w) & =p(u-v)+p(v-w)\\
 & \geq p(u-w)\\
 & =d(u,w).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The metric 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 induced by a norm 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 has additional properties that are not true of general metrics.
 These are 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Translation Invariance) 
\begin_inset Formula $d(u+w,v+w)=d(u,v)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v,w\in V$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Scaling Property) 
\begin_inset Formula $d(au,av)=|a|d(u,v)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in V$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Convserely, if a metric has these properties, then 
\begin_inset Formula $d(u,0)$
\end_inset

 is a norm.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Limit of a Sequence in a Metric Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 in a metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
converges to 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, and write 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}x_{n}=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

, if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $N=N_{\varepsilon}\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\geq N\text{ implies }d(x_{n},x)<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset

If a sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 has a limit, then we say that the sequence is 
\series bold
convergent
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremconsecutive}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 in a metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 converges, then 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{n},x_{n+1})\to0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

.
 From the triangle inequality, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d(x_{n},x_{n+1})\leq d(x_{n},x)+d(x,x_{n+1})=d(x_{n},x)+d(x_{n+1},x).
\]

\end_inset

The two terms on the right get small when 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is large, so 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{n},x_{n+1})$
\end_inset

 gets small when 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is large.
 To be precise, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon/2>0$
\end_inset

 there's an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\geq1$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq N$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{m},x)<\varepsilon/2$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\geq N\text{ implies }n+1\geq N\text{ implies }d(x_{n},x_{n+1})\leq d(x_{n},x)+d(x_{n+1},x)<\frac{\varepsilon}{2}+\frac{\varepsilon}{2}=\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every subsequence of a convergent sequence in a metric space is also convergent
, with the same limit.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n_{i}})$
\end_inset

 be a subsequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}=x_{n_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 We want ot show 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\to x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{n},x)<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Since the interegers 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset

 are increasing, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}\geq N$
\end_inset

 if we go out far enough: there's an 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $i\geq I$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}\geq N$
\end_inset

 which imlpies 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{n_{i}},x)<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $d(y_{i},x)<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\to x$
\end_inset

.
  
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In a metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

, if two sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n}')$
\end_inset

 converge to the same value, then 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{n},x_{n}')\to0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}'\to x$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists some integer 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\geq N\text{ implies }d(x_{n},x)<\frac{\varepsilon}{2}\text{ and }d(x_{n}',x)<\frac{\varepsilon}{2}.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\geq N\text{ implies }d(x_{n},x_{n}')\leq d(x_{n},x)+d(x,x_{n}')<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 On 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, because the metrics 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{E}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 are each bounded above by a constant multiple of the other, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{E}(x_{n},x)\to0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}(x_{n},x)\to0$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon/\sqrt{m}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\geq N\text{ implies }d_{\infty}(x_{n},x)<\frac{\varepsilon}{\sqrt{m}},
\]

\end_inset

and since 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{E}(x_{n},x)\leq\sqrt{m}d_{\infty}(x_{n},x)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\geq N\text{ implies }d_{E}(x_{n},x)<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset

The converse is shown the same way.
 Therefore convergence of sequences in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 for both metrics means the same thing (with the same limits).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $C[0,1]$
\end_inset

 consider the sequence of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.This sequence converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 in the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}$
\end_inset

 but not in the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{1}(x^{n},0)=\int_{0}^{1}|x^{n}|dx=\frac{1}{n+1}\to0,\qquad d_{\infty}(x^{n},0)=\max_{0\leq x\leq1}|x^{n}|=1.
\]

\end_inset

In fact the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $C[0,1]$
\end_inset

 has no limit at all relative to the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 To prove 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{n})$
\end_inset

 has no limit in 
\begin_inset Formula $(C[0,1],d_{\infty})$
\end_inset

, not just that the constant function 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 is not a limit, we seek a property that all convergent sequences satisfy
 and the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $(C[0,1],d_{\infty})$
\end_inset

 does not satisfy.
 This will be provided to us in the next section.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cauchy Sequences and Completeness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremconsecutive})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that for a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 in a metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 to converge, it is necessary that 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{n},x_{n+1})\to0$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, this condition is not sufficient.
 Indeed, in 
\begin_inset Formula $C[0,1]$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{\infty}(x^{n},x^{n+1})=\max_{0\leq x\leq1}|x^{n}-x^{n+1}|=\max_{0\leq x\leq1}(x^{n}-x^{n+1}),
\]

\end_inset

To find the maximal value, we first compute the derivative
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dx}\left(x^{n}-x^{n+1}\right)=nx^{n-1}-(n+1)x^{n}=x^{n-1}(n-(n+1)x).
\]

\end_inset

Setting this equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, we have either 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x=n/(n+1)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}-x^{n+1}=x^{n}(1-x)$
\end_inset

 is always positive on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

, it must be maximized on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=n/(n+1)$
\end_inset

, where the value is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{n}{n+1}\right)^{n}\left(1-\frac{n}{n+1}\right)\sim\frac{1}{e}\left(\frac{1}{n+1}\right)\to0.
\]

\end_inset

Thus, we do have 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}(x^{n},x^{n+1})\to0$
\end_inset

.
 However we shall see shortly that this sequence does not converge under
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 metric.
 Indeed, by the exact same reasoning in the proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremconsecutive})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we should also have 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}(x^{n},x^{2n})\to0$
\end_inset

.
 But
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{\infty}(x^{n},x^{2n})=\max_{0\leq x\leq1}|x^{n}-x^{2n}|=\max_{0\leq x\leq1}(x^{n}(1-x^{n})),
\]

\end_inset

has its maximum value at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1/\sqrt[n]{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}(1-x^{n})=1/4$
\end_inset

, which is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 This proves that 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{n})$
\end_inset

 has not limit in 
\begin_inset Formula $(C[0,1],d_{\infty})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremconvergenceimpliescauchy}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a convergent sequence in a metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

, then the terms of the sequence become 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

uniformly close
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m,n\geq N\text{ implies }d(x_{n},x_{m})<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\lim_{n\to\infty}x_{n}$
\end_inset

, the triangle inequality tells us for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d(x_{m},x_{n})\leq d(x_{m},x)+d(x,x_{n})=d(x_{m},x)+d(x_{n},x).
\]

\end_inset

We now make an 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon/2$
\end_inset

 argument.
 For every 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there's an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{n},x)<\varepsilon/2$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d(x_{m},x_{n}) & \leq d(x_{m},x)+d(x,x_{n})\\
 & <\frac{\varepsilon}{2}+\frac{\varepsilon}{2}\\
 & =\varepsilon.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 in a metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
Cauchy sequence 
\series default
if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $N=N_{\varepsilon}\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m,n\geq N\text{ implies }d(x_{m},x_{n})<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{corconvergentinXcauchy}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 is a metric space and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 given the induced metric 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid_{Y}$
\end_inset

, then any sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 that converges in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a Cauchy sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $(Y,d\mid_{Y})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 that converges in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Cauchy in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremconvergenceimpliescauchy})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Since the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the metric we are using on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, the Cauchy property of 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be viewed as the Cauchy property in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,\infty)$
\end_inset

 as a metric space using the absolute value metric induced from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n\to0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, but the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/n)$
\end_inset

 has no limit in 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,\infty)$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $0\notin(0,\infty)$
\end_inset

.
 The sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/n)$
\end_inset

 is a Cauchy sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,\infty)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Corollary~(
\backslash
ref{corconvergentinXcauchy})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 but it is not a convergent sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,\infty)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a sequence in a metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{n},x_{n+1})\leq ar^{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0<r<1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a Cauchy sequence.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq m<n$
\end_inset

, a massive use of the triangle inequality tells us 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d(x_{m},x_{n}) & \leq d(x_{m},x_{m+1})+d(x_{m+1},x_{m+2})+\cdots+d(x_{n-1},x_{n})\\
 & \leq ar^{m}+ar^{m+1}+\cdots+ar^{n-1}\\
 & <\sum_{k=m}^{\infty}ar^{k}\\
 & =\frac{ar^{m}}{1-r}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $0<r<1$
\end_inset

, the terms 
\begin_inset Formula $ar^{n}$
\end_inset

 tend to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Now if we pick an 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

, choose 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 large enough that 
\begin_inset Formula $ar^{N}<(1-r)\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\geq N$
\end_inset

, without loss of generality 
\begin_inset Formula $m\leq n$
\end_inset

 so by our prior calculation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d(x_{m},x_{n}) & <\frac{ar^{m}}{1-r}\\
 & \leq\frac{ar^{N}}{1-r}\\
 & <\varepsilon.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Complete Metric Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
complete 
\series default
if every Cauchy sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 converges in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

: if 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is Cauchy in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 then there's an 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Completions exist
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our goal in this subsection is to prove the following theorem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a metric space.
 Then a completion of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 exists.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X}$
\end_inset

 denote the set of Cauchy sequences in the given metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We say two elements 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n}),(y_{n})\in C_{X}$
\end_inset

 are 
\series bold
equivalent
\series default
, written 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})\sim(y_{n})$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x_{n},y_{n})\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that this is an equivalence relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 The only nontrivial part to check is transitivity: Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})\sim(y_{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{n})\sim(z_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(x_{n},z_{n})\leq\rho(x_{n},y_{n})+\rho(y_{n},z_{n})\to0+0
\]

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X}/\sim$
\end_inset

 to be the set of equivalence classes in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X}$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

.
 Note that there is a natural map of sets 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota_{X}:X\to C_{X}/\sim,
\]

\end_inset

which assigns to each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, the equivalence class of constant sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $(x)\in C_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{X}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{X}(x)=\iota_{X}(x')$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(x)\sim(x')$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x,x')\to0$
\end_inset

 forces 
\begin_inset Formula $x=x'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We now must enhance the structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X}/\sim$
\end_inset

 by giving it a metric (with respect to which we'll easily see 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{X}$
\end_inset

 is an isometry with dense image).
 We first define a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pseudo-metric
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on the set 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Let's first define what we mean by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pseudo-metric
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
pseudo-metric 
\series default
on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $d:S\times S\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 which satisfies the following three properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $d(s,s)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $d(s,t)=d(t,s)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s,t\in S$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $d(s,u)\leq d(s,t)+d(t,u)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s,t,u\in S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The same proof as in the metric case shows that a pseudo-metric is positive-defi
nite (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $d(s,t)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s,t\in S$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The only difference between a metric and a pseudo-metric is that a pseudo-metric
 might satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $d(s,t)=0$
\end_inset

 for some pair 
\begin_inset Formula $s,t\in S$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $s\neq t$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(t_{n})$
\end_inset

 are Cauchy sequences in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\rho(s_{n},t_{n}))$
\end_inset

 is a convergent sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We show that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\rho(s_{n},t_{n}))$
\end_inset

 is a Cauchy sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(t_{n})$
\end_inset

 are Cauchy sequences, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(s_{n},s_{m})<\varepsilon/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(t_{n},t_{m})<\varepsilon/2$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n,m\geq N$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(s_{n},t_{n})\leq\rho(s_{n},s_{m})+\rho(s_{m},t_{m})+\rho(t_{m},t_{n})$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(s_{n},t_{n})-\rho(s_{m},t_{m})\leq\rho(s_{n},s_{m})+\rho(t_{m},t_{n}),
\]

\end_inset

and implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(s_{m},t_{m})-\rho(s_{n},t_{n})\leq\rho(s_{m},s_{n})+\rho(t_{n},t_{m}).
\]

\end_inset

Thus, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n,m\geq N$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|\rho(s_{n},t_{n})-\rho(s_{m},t_{m})|\leq\rho(s_{n},s_{m})+\rho(t_{m},t_{n})<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the lemma established, the following definition makes sense:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n}),(y_{n})\in C_{X}$
\end_inset

, we define the 
\series bold
pseudo-distance 
\series default
between them to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d((x_{n}),(y_{n}))=\lim_{n\to\infty}\rho(x_{n},y_{n}).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pseudo-distance defined is a pseudo-metric since it inherits the properties
 these from 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{corpseudo}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2},c_{1}',c_{2}'\in C_{X}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}\sim c_{j}'$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d(c_{1},c_{2})=d(c_{1}',c_{2}')$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, the pseudo-metric 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X}$
\end_inset

 respects the equivalence relation.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}\sim c_{j}'$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $d(c_{j},c_{j}')=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d(c_{1},c_{2}) & \leq d(c_{1},c_{1}')+d(c_{1}',c_{2}')+d(c_{2}',c_{2})\\
 & =d(c_{1}',c_{2}').
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similarly,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d(c_{1}',c_{2}') & \leq d(c_{1}',c_{1})+d(c_{1},c_{2})+d(c_{2},c_{2}')\\
 & =d(c_{1},c_{2}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $d(c_{1},c_{2})=d(c_{1}',c_{2}')$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $X'=C_{X}/\sim$
\end_inset

 and define the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho':X'\times X'\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho'(\xi_{1},\xi_{2})=d(c_{1},c_{2})
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2}\in C_{X}$
\end_inset

 are respective representative elements for 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{1},\xi_{2}\in X'=C_{X}/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

This definition is well-defined in view of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Corollary~(
\backslash
ref{corpseudo})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In fact, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho':X'\times X'\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a metric since it inherits the pseudo-metric properties from 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, and modding out by the equivalence relation ensures that we have identity
 of indiscernibles.
 Note that we also have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho'(\iota_{X}(x),\iota_{X}(y))=\rho(x,y)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{X}:X\to X'$
\end_inset

 is an isometric embedding.
 In fact the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $X'$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, fix a choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\in X'$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a representative Cauchy sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})\in C_{X}$
\end_inset

 for the equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\in X'$
\end_inset

.
 Then the sequence of elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{X}(x_{n})\in\iota_{X}(X)\subseteq X'$
\end_inset

 has limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Open and Closed Subsets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we generalize open and closed intervals in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 to open and closed balls of a metric space.
 Throughout, let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 be a metric space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r\geq0$
\end_inset

, the 
\series bold
open ball 
\series default
with center 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{B}_{r}(a)=\{x\in X\mid d(a,x)<r\},
\]

\end_inset

and the 
\series bold
closed ball 
\series default
with center 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{B}_{r}[a]=\{x\in X\mid d(a,x)\leq r\}.
\]

\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $B(a,0)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{B}(a,0)=\{a\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
bounded 
\series default
if it is contained in some ball 
\begin_inset Formula $B(a,r)$
\end_inset

.
 A subset that is not bounded is called 
\series bold
unbounded
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset X$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
open 
\series default
if for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

 there's an 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $B(x,r)\subset U$
\end_inset

.
 We also consider the empty subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to be an open subset.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Pseudometric Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
pseudometric 
\series default
on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}\colon X\times X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 which satisfies the following three properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Reflexivity) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(x,x)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Symmetry) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(x,y)=\mathrm{d}(y,x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Triangle Inequality) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(x,z)\leq\mathrm{d}(x,y)+\mathrm{d}(y,z)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z\in X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

 is a pseudometric on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then we call the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
pseudometric space
\series default
.
 If the pseudometric is understood from context, then we often denote a
 pseudometric space by 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Given the three axioms above, we also have 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,y)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =d(x,x)\\
 & \leq d(x,y)+d(y,x)\\
 & =d(x,y)+d(x,y)\\
 & =2d(x,y).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,y)\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Topology Induced by Pseudometric Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{proppseudometrictopbasis}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 be a pseudometric space.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

, define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{B}_{r}^{\mathrm{d}}(x):=\{y\in X\mid\mathrm{d}(x,y)<r\},
\]

\end_inset

and let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{B}^{\mathrm{d}}=\{\mathrm{B}_{r}(x)\mid x\in X\text{ and }r>0\}.
\]

\end_inset

Finally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(\mathcal{B}^{\mathrm{d}})$
\end_inset

 be the smallest topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}^{\mathrm{d}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}^{\mathrm{d}}$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(\mathcal{B}^{\mathrm{d}})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We often remove the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

 in the superscript in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}^{\mathrm{d}}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}^{\mathrm{d}}$
\end_inset

 whenever context is clear.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 covers 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\subseteq\bigcup_{x\in X}\mathrm{B}_{r}(x).
\]

\end_inset

Next, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r'}(x')$
\end_inset

 be two members of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 which have nontrivial intersection and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x''\in\mathrm{B}_{r}(x)\cap\mathrm{B}_{r'}(x')$
\end_inset

.
 Set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r''=\min\{r'-\mathrm{d}(x',x''),r-\mathrm{d}(x,x'')\}.
\]

\end_inset

We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r''}(x'')\subseteq\mathrm{B}_{r}(x)\cap\mathrm{B}_{r'}(x')$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, assume without loss of generality that 
\begin_inset Formula $r''=r-\mathrm{d}(x,x'')$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathrm{B}_{r''}(x'')$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{d}(y,x) & \leq\mathrm{d}(y,x'')+\mathrm{d}(x'',x)\\
 & <r-\mathrm{d}(x,x'')+\mathrm{d}(x'',x)\\
 & =r-\mathrm{d}(x'',x)+\mathrm{d}(x'',x)\\
 & =r
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathrm{B}_{r}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{d}(y,x') & \leq\mathrm{d}(y,x'')+\mathrm{d}(x'',x')\\
 & <r'-\mathrm{d}(x',x'')+\mathrm{d}(x'',x')\\
 & =r'-\mathrm{d}(x'',x')+\mathrm{d}(x'',x')\\
 & =r'
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathrm{B}_{r'}(x')$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r''}(x'')\subseteq\mathrm{B}_{r}(x)\cap\mathrm{B}_{r'}(x')$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(\mathcal{B})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The topology 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(\mathcal{B})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{proppseudometrictopbasis})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is called the
\series bold
 topology
\series default
 
\series bold
induced by the pseudometric 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 We also denote this topology by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\mathrm{d}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Subspace topology agrees with topology induced by pseudometric
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 be a pseudometric space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq X$
\end_inset

.
 Then the pseudometric on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 restricts to a pseudometric on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 We denote this restriction by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}|_{A}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus there are two natural topologies on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 One is the subspace is the subspace topology given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau\cap A:=\{U\cap A\mid U\in\tau\}.
\]

\end_inset

The other is the topology induced by the pseudometric 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}|_{A}$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{\mathrm{d}|_{A}}:=\tau(\mathcal{B}^{\mathrm{d}}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next proposition tells us that these are actually the same.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 be a pseudometric space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq X$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{\mathrm{d}}\cap A=\tau_{\mathrm{d}|_{A}}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{B}_{r}^{\mathrm{d}|_{A}}(a) & =\{b\in A\mid\mathrm{d}|_{A}(a,b)<r\}\\
 & =\{b\in A\mid\mathrm{d}(a,b)<r\}\\
 & =A\cap\{x\in X\mid\mathrm{d}(a,x)<r\}\\
 & =A\cap\mathrm{B}_{r}^{\mathrm{d}}(a).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\mathrm{d}|_{A}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\mathrm{d}}\cap A$
\end_inset

 have the same basis, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\mathrm{d}}\cap A=\tau_{\mathrm{d}|_{A}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Convergence in 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Concepts like convergence and completion still make sense in pseudometric
 spaces.
 This is because these are purely topological concepts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 be a pseudometric space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\varepsilon}\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We write 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 in the subscript to remind the reader that 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Usually we omit 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 in the subscript and just write 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\geq N_{\varepsilon}\text{ implies }\mathrm{d}(x_{n},x)<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset

In this case, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
convergent 
\series default
and that it 
\series bold
converges 
\series default
to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 We denote this by 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim\limits _{n\to\infty}x_{n}=x$
\end_inset

, or even just 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
Cauchy 
\series default
if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\varepsilon}\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n,m\geq N_{\varepsilon}\text{ implies }\mathrm{d}(x_{n},x_{m})<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Completeness in 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a metric space, every Cauchy sequence is convergence but the converse
 may not hold.
 The same thing is true for pseudometric spaces since the proof is purely
 topological.
 Let's go over the proof again:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is Cauchy.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}(x_{n},x)<\varepsilon/2.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $n,m\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{d}(x_{n},x_{m}) & \leq\mathrm{d}(x_{n},x)+\mathrm{d}(x,x_{m})\\
 & <\varepsilon/2+\varepsilon/2\\
 & =\varepsilon.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is Cauchy.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Thus, the concept of completeness makes sense in a pseudometric space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 be a pseudometric space.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
complete 
\series default
if every Cauchy sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 is a convergent.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Metric Obtained by Pseudometric
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unless otherwise specified, we let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 be a pseudometric space throughout the remainder of this section.
 There is a natural way to obtain a metric space from 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 which we now describe as follows: define a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\sim y\text{ if and only if }\mathrm{d}(x,y)=0.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence relation.
 Indeed, we have reflexivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(x,x)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we have symmetry of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(x,y)=\mathrm{d}(y,x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

, and we have transitivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the triangle inequality: if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\sim z$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{d}(x,z) & \leq\mathrm{d}(x,y)+\mathrm{d}(y,z)\\
 & =0+0\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(x,z)=0$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Therefore we may consider the quotient space of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with respect to the equivalence relation above.
 We shall denote this quotient space by 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]:=X\slash\sim$
\end_inset

.
 A coset in 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

 which is represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 will be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]$
\end_inset

.
 There is a natural 
\series bold
projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon X\to[X]$
\end_inset

 
\series default
that sends 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 to its equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is surjective, any subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

 has the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[A]=\{[a]\in[X]\mid a\in A\}.
\]

\end_inset

We are ready to define the metric on 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{d}]\colon[X]\times[X]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[\mathrm{d}]([x],[y])=\mathrm{d}(x,y)\label{eq:welldefinedpseudometrictometric}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $[x],[y]\in[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{d}]$
\end_inset

 is a metric on 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

.
 It is called the metric 
\series bold
induced 
\series default
by the pseudometric.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first show that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:welldefinedpseudometrictometric})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well-defined.
 Indeed, choose different coset representatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[y]$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y'$
\end_inset

 respectively (so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(x,x')=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(y,y')=0$
\end_inset

).
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[\mathrm{d}]([x'],[y']) & =\mathrm{d}(x',y')\\
 & \leq\mathrm{d}(x',x)+\mathrm{d}(x,y)+\mathrm{d}(y,y')\\
 & =\mathrm{d}(x,y)\\
 & =[\mathrm{d}]([x],[y]).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{d}]$
\end_inset

 is well-defined.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{d}]$
\end_inset

 is in fact a metric on 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

.
 First we check 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{d}]$
\end_inset

 is symmetric.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $[x],[y]\in[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[\mathrm{d}]([x],[y]) & =\mathrm{d}(x,y)\\
 & =\mathrm{d}(y,x)\\
 & =[\mathrm{d}]([y],[x]).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{d}]$
\end_inset

 is symmetric.
 Next we check 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{d}]$
\end_inset

 satisfies triangle inequality.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $[x],[y],[z]\in[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[\mathrm{d}]([x],[z]) & =\mathrm{d}(x,z)\\
 & \leq\mathrm{d}(x,y)+\mathrm{d}(y,z)\\
 & =[\mathrm{d}]([x],[y])+[\mathrm{d}]([y],[z]).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{d}]$
\end_inset

 satisfies triangle inequality.
 Finally we check 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{d}]$
\end_inset

 satisfies identify of indiscernables.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $[x],[y]\in[X]$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{d}]([x],[y])=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =[\mathrm{d}]([x],[y])\\
 & =\mathrm{d}(x,y)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

 by definition.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]=[y]$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{d}]$
\end_inset

 satisfies identify of indiscernables.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Completeness in 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to completeness in 
\begin_inset Formula $([X],[\mathrm{d}])$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As in the case of the pseudometric 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

, the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{d}]$
\end_inset

 induces a topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

.
 We denote this topology by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{[\mathrm{d}]}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 is complete if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $([X],[\mathrm{d}])$
\end_inset

 is complete.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 is complete.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $([x_{n}])$
\end_inset

 be a Cauchy sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $([X],[\mathrm{d}])$
\end_inset

.
 We claim 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a Cauchy sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\mathrm{d}]([x_{n}],[x_{m}])<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{d}(x_{n},x_{m}) & =[\mathrm{d}]([x_{n}],[x_{m}])\\
 & <\varepsilon.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a Cauchy sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 is complete, the sequence converges to a (not necessarily unique) 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Then we claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $[x_{n}]\to[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}(x_{n},x)<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[\mathrm{d}]([x_{n}],[x]) & =\mathrm{d}(x_{n},x)\\
 & <\varepsilon.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $[x_{n}]\to[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $([X],[\mathrm{d}])$
\end_inset

 is complete.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $([X],[\mathrm{d}])$
\end_inset

 is complete.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a Cauchy sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

.
 We claim 
\begin_inset Formula $([x_{n}])$
\end_inset

 is a Cauchy sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $([X],\mathrm{[d}])$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}(x_{n},x_{m})<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[\mathrm{d}]([x_{n}],[x_{m}]) & =\mathrm{d}(x_{n},x_{m})\\
 & <\varepsilon.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a Cauchy sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $([X],[\mathrm{d}])$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $([X],[\mathrm{d}])$
\end_inset

 is complete, the sequence converges to a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]\in[X]$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

 (in fact it converges to any 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\sim x$
\end_inset

).
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\mathrm{d}]([x_{n}],[x])<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{d}(x_{n},x) & =[\mathrm{d}]([x_{n}],[x])\\
 & <\varepsilon.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 is complete.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Quotient Topology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that we view 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as a topological space with toplogy 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\mathrm{d}}$
\end_inset

; the topology induced by the pseudometric 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

.
 It turns out that there are two natural topologies on 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

.
 One such topology is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{[\mathrm{d}]}$
\end_inset

; the topology induced by the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{d}]$
\end_inset

.
 The other topology is called the 
\series bold
quotient topology
\series default
 
\series bold
with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset


\series default
, and is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $[\tau_{\mathrm{d}}]$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $[\tau_{\mathrm{d}}]$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\tau_{\mathrm{d}}]=\{[A]\subseteq[X]\mid\pi^{-1}([A])\in\tau_{\mathrm{d}}\}.
\]

\end_inset

In other words, we declare a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $[A]$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

 to be open in 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

 if and only if
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi^{-1}([A]) & =\{x\in X\mid x\sim a\text{ for some }a\in A\}\\
 & =\{x\in X\mid\mathrm{d}(x,a)=0\text{ for some }a\in A\}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{-1}(\emptyset)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{-1}([X])=X$
\end_inset

, we see that both 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

 are open in 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}\left(\bigcup_{i\in I}[A_{i}]\right)=\bigcup_{i\in I}\pi^{-1}([A_{i}])\text{ and }\pi^{-1}\left(\bigcap_{i\in I}[A_{i}]\right)=\bigcap_{i\in I}\pi^{-1}([A_{i}]),
\]

\end_inset

we see that the collection of open sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

 is closed under arbitrary unions and finite intersections.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $[\tau_{\mathrm{d}}]$
\end_inset

 is indeed a topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $[\tau_{\mathrm{d}}]$
\end_inset

 was defined in such a way that it makes the projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon X\to[X]$
\end_inset

 continous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Universal Mapping Property For Quotient Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quotient spaces satisfy the following universal mapping property.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propumpforquotientspace}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be any continuous function which is constant on each equivalence class.
 Then there exists a unique continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $[f]\colon[X]\to Y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f=[f]\circ\pi$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $[f]\colon[X]\to Y$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[f]([x])=f(x)\label{eq:welldefinedinducedq-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 We first show that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{welldefinedinducedq-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well-defined.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 are two different representatives of the same coset (so 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim x'$
\end_inset

).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=f(x')$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 was assumed to be constant on equivalence classes, and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[f]([x']) & =f(x')\\
 & =f(x)\\
 & =[f]([x]).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{welldefinedinducedq})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well-defined.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $[f]$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}(V)=\pi^{-1}\left([f]^{-1}(V)\right)
\]

\end_inset

is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 By the definition of quotient topology, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $[f]^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $[f]$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finally, we want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f=[f]\circ\pi$
\end_inset

 holds.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
([f]\circ\pi)(x) & =[f](\pi(x))\\
 & =[f]([x])\\
 & =f(x).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $[f]\circ\pi=f$
\end_inset

.
 This establishes existence of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For uniqueness, assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}\colon[X]\to Y$
\end_inset

 is a continuous function such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\overline{f}\circ\pi$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}\neq[f]$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]\in[X]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}[x]\neq[f][x]$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(x) & =(\overline{f}\circ\pi)(x)\\
 & =\overline{f}(\pi(x))\\
 & =\overline{f}([x])\\
 & \neq[f]([x])\\
 & =f(x),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which gives us a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propumpforquotientspace})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that we have the following bijection of sets
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ f\colon X\to Y\mid f\text{ is continuous and constant on equivalence classes}\right\} \cong\left\{ \text{continuous functions from }[X]\text{ to }Y\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

In particular, if we want to study continuous functions out of 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

, then we just need to study the continuous functions out of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 which are constant on equivalence classes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(Y,\mathrm{d}_{Y})$
\end_inset

 is a metric space and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon(X,\mathrm{d})\to(Y,\mathrm{d}_{Y})$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is constant on equivalence classes.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,x'\in X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim x'$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(x,x')=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}(x,y)<\delta\text{ implies }\mathrm{d}_{Y}(f(x),f(y))<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset

We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=f(x')$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Open Equivalence Relation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
open 
\series default
if the projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon X\to[X]$
\end_inset

 is open.
 In other words, the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if for every open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}(\pi(U))=\bigcup_{x\in U}[x]
\]

\end_inset

of all points equivalent to some point of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is open.
 The imporance of open equivalence relations is that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{B}$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathscr{B}]$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmaballsgotoballs}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{B}_{r}(x)=\pi^{-1}([\mathrm{B}_{r}(x)]).
\]

\end_inset

In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is an open mapping.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{B}_{r}(x) & \subseteq\pi^{-1}\left(\pi\left(\mathrm{B}_{r}(x)\right)\right)\\
 & =\pi^{-1}([\mathrm{B}_{r}(x)]).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

For the reverse inclusion, let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\pi^{-1}([\mathrm{B}_{r}(x)])$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(y,z)=0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathrm{B}_{r}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Choose such a 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathrm{B}_{r}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{d}(y,x) & \leq\mathrm{d}(y,z)+\mathrm{d}(z,x)\\
 & =\mathrm{d}(z,x)\\
 & <r
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies implies 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathrm{B}_{r}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}([\mathrm{B}_{r}(x)])\subseteq\mathrm{B}_{r}(x).
\]

\end_inset

Thus each subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

 of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{B}_{r}(x)]$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is an open mapping, let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Since the set of all open balls is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\mathrm{d}}$
\end_inset

, we can cover 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 by open balls, say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\bigcup_{i\in I}\mathrm{B}_{r_{i}}(x_{i}).
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi(U) & =\pi\left(\bigcup_{i\in I}\mathrm{B}_{r_{i}}(x_{i})\right)\\
 & =\bigcup_{i\in I}\pi\left(\mathrm{B}_{r_{i}}(x_{i})\right)\\
 & =\bigcup_{i\in I}[\mathrm{B}_{r_{i}}(x_{i})]\\
 & \in[\tau_{\mathrm{d}}].
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is an open mapping.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Quotient Topology Agrees With Metric Topology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 With the notation as above, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\tau_{\mathrm{d}}]=\tau_{[\mathrm{d}]}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first note that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[\mathrm{B}_{r}(x)] & =\{[y]\in[X]\mid y\in\mathrm{B}_{r}(x)\}\\
 & =\{[y]\in[X]\mid\mathrm{d}(y,x)<r\}\\
 & =\{[y]\in[X]\mid[\mathrm{d}]([y],[x])<r\}\\
 & =\mathrm{B}_{r}([x]).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{[\mathrm{d}]}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[\tau_{\mathrm{d}}]$
\end_inset

 share a common basis.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{[\mathrm{d}]}=[\tau_{\mathrm{d}}]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Quotient Topology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\tau)$
\end_inset

 be a topological space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 be an equivalence relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We denote 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]:=X\slash\sim$
\end_inset

.
 A coset in 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

 which is represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 will be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]$
\end_inset

.
 There is a natural 
\series bold
projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:X\to[X]$
\end_inset

 
\series default
that sends 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 to its equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is surjective, any subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

 has the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[A]=\{[a]\in[X]\mid a\in A\}.
\]

\end_inset

With these considerations in mind, we define a topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

 called the 
\series bold
quotient topology
\series default
 
\series bold
with respect to the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset


\series default
, which we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $[\tau]$
\end_inset

, by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\tau]=\{[A]\subseteq[X]\mid\pi^{-1}([A])\in\tau\}.
\]

\end_inset

In other words, we declare a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $[A]$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

 to be open in 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi^{-1}([A]) & =\{x\in X\mid x\sim a\text{ for some }a\in A\}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{-1}(\emptyset)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{-1}([X])=X$
\end_inset

, we see that both 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

 are open in 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}\left(\bigcup_{i\in I}[A_{i}]\right)=\bigcup_{i\in I}\pi^{-1}([A_{i}])\text{ and }\pi^{-1}\left(\bigcap_{i\in I}[A_{i}]\right)=\bigcap_{i\in I}\pi^{-1}([A_{i}]),
\]

\end_inset

we see that the collection of open sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

 is closed under arbitrary unions and finite intersections.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $[\tau]$
\end_inset

 is indeed a topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $[\tau]$
\end_inset

 was defined in such a way that it makes the projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon X\to[X]$
\end_inset

 continuous.
 Also, any open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

 can be represented by an open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $[A]$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Denote 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\pi^{-1}([A])$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $[U]=[A]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{B}$
\end_inset

 be a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathscr{B}]$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{B}$
\end_inset

 covers 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $[U]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[V]$
\end_inset

 be two elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{B}$
\end_inset

 and assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 are open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Continuity of a Map on a Quotient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a continuous function.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is constant on each equivalence class, then it induces a map 
\begin_inset Formula $[f]\colon[X]\to Y$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[f][x]=f(x)\label{eq:welldefinedinducedq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 To see that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{welldefinedinducedq})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well-defined, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 are two different representatives of the same coset (so 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim x'$
\end_inset

).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=f(x')$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 was assumed to be constant on equivalence classes, and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[f][x'] & =f(x')\\
 & =f(x)\\
 & =[f][x].
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{welldefinedinducedq})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well-defined.
 We also have continuity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $[f]\colon[X]\to Y$
\end_inset

 is continuous if and only if the map 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $[f]$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous since 
\begin_inset Formula $f=[f]\circ\pi$
\end_inset

 is a composition of two continuous functions.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}(V)=\pi^{-1}\left([f]^{-1}(V)\right)
\]

\end_inset

is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 By the definition of quotient topology, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $[f]^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $[X]$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $[f]$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Identification of a Subset to a Point
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a subspace of a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we can define a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by declaring 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\sim x\text{ for all }x\in X\text{ and }x\sim y\text{ for all }x,y\in A.
\]

\end_inset

This is an equivalence relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We say that the quotient space 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by 
\series bold
identifying 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to a point
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be the unit interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I/\sim$
\end_inset

 be the quotient space obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 by identifying the two points 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

 to a point.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 the unit circle in the complex plane.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:I\to S^{1}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=e^{2\pi ix}$
\end_inset

, assumes the same value at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, and so induces a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}:I/\sim\to S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 As the continuous image of a compact set 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, the quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $I/\sim$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is a continuous bijection from the compact space 
\begin_inset Formula $I/\sim$
\end_inset

 to the Hausdorff space 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence it is a homeomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Open Equivalence Relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

An equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
open 
\series default
if the projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:X\to X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is open.
 In other words, the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if for every open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}(\pi(U))=\bigcup_{x\in U}[x]
\]

\end_inset

of all points equivalent to some point of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is open.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 be the equivalence relation on the real line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 that identifies the two points 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}/\sim$
\end_inset

 be the projection map.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is not an open map.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be the open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(-2,0)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}(\pi(V))=(-2,0)\cup\{1\},
\]

\end_inset

which is not open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Given an equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be the subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

 that defines the relation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=\{(x,y)\in X\times X\mid x\sim y\}.
\]

\end_inset

We call 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
graph 
\series default
of the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremquotientishausdorff}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an open equivalence relation on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then the quotient space 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff if and only if the graph 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 There is a sequence of equivalent statements: 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $(X\times X)\backslash R$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

 iff for every 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in(X\times X)\backslash R$
\end_inset

, there is a basic open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\times V$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(U\times V)\cap R=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 iff for every pair 
\begin_inset Formula $x\not\sim y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, there exist neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that no element of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 iff for any two points 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]\neq[y]$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

, there exist neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U)\cap\pi(V)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We now show that this last statement is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 being Hausdorff.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an open equivalence relation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(V)$
\end_inset

 are disjoint open sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[y]$
\end_inset

 respectively, so 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]\neq[y]$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exist disjoint open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[y]\in B$
\end_inset

.
 By the surjectivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\pi(\pi^{-1}A)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\pi(\pi^{-1}B)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\pi^{-1}A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\pi^{-1}B$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in V$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\pi(U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\pi(V)$
\end_inset

 are disjoint open sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 be an open equivalence relation on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}=\{B_{\alpha}\}$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then its image 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\pi(B_{\alpha})\}$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is an open map, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\pi(B(\alpha)\}$
\end_inset

 is a collection of open sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be an open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]\in W$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\pi^{-1}(W)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{-1}(W)$
\end_inset

 is open, there is a basic open set 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B\subset\pi^{-1}(W)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]=\pi(x)\in\pi(B)\subset W$
\end_inset

, which proves that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\pi(B_{\alpha})\}$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $S/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an open equivalence relation on a second-countable space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then the quotient space is second-countable.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Quotients by Group Actions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Many important manifolds are constructed as quotients by actions of groups
 on other manifolds, and this often provides a useful way to understand
 spaces that may have been constructed by other means.
 As a basic example, the Klein bottle will be defined as a quotient of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}\times S^{1}$
\end_inset

 by the action of a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 The circle as defined concretely in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to the quotient of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by additive translation by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 a discrete group.
 A right action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
continuous 
\series default
if for each 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 the action map 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to X$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto x.g$
\end_inset

 is continuous (and hence a homeomorphism, as the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

 gives an inverse).
 The action is 
\series bold
free 
\series default
if for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 the stabilizer subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g\in G\mid x.g=x\}$
\end_inset

 is the trivial subgroup (in other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $x.g=x$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g=1$
\end_inset

).
 The action is 
\series bold
properly discontinuous
\series default
 when it is continuous for the discrete topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 admits an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 so that the 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-translate 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}.g$
\end_inset

 meets 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 for only finitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A right action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is continuous if 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:X\times G\to X$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has the discrete topology.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose we have a right action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 which is continuous.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{g}:=g^{-1}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}(U)=\bigcup_{g\in G}U_{g}\times\{g\},
\]

\end_inset

which is open.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is continuous and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{g}:=g^{-1}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}(U)\cap X\times\{g\}=U_{g}\times\{g\},
\]

\end_inset

which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is continuous since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{-1}(U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times\{g\}$
\end_inset

 are open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a locally Hausdorff space, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 on the right via a properly discontinuous action.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we get an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 meets 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}.g$
\end_inset

 for only finitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 This property is unaffected by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 with a smaller open subset around 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, so by the locally Hausdorff property we can assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff.
 The key is that we can do better: there exists an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}\subseteq U_{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}$
\end_inset

 meets 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}.g$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=x.g$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, if the action is also free then 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}$
\end_inset

 is disjoint from 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}.g$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g\neq1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To find 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},\dots,g_{n}\in G$
\end_inset

 be an enumeration of the finite set of elements 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 meets 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}.g$
\end_inset

.
 For any open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq U_{x}$
\end_inset

 we can only have 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U.g\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 equal to one of the 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

's, so it suffices to show that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x.g_{i}\in U_{x}\backslash\{x\}$
\end_inset

 there is an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\subseteq U_{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cap(U_{i}).g_{i}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 (and then we may take 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}$
\end_inset

 to be the intersection of the 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

's over the finitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x.g_{i}\neq x$
\end_inset

).
 By the Hausdorff property of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

, when 
\begin_inset Formula $x.g_{i}\in U_{x}\backslash\{x\}$
\end_inset

 there exist disjoint opens 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i},V_{i}'\subseteq U_{x}$
\end_inset

 around 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x.g_{i}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 By continuity of the action on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}\in G$
\end_inset

 there is an open 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{i}\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 around 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(W_{i}).g_{i}\subseteq V'_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=W_{i}\cap V_{i}$
\end_inset

 is disjoint from 
\begin_inset Formula $V'_{i}$
\end_inset

 yet satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{i}).g_{i}\subseteq V'_{i}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cap(U_{i}).g_{i}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 This completes the construction of 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The interest in free and properly discontinuous actions is that for such
 actions in the locally Hausdorff case we may find an open 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 around each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 is disjoint from 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}.g$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $g\neq1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, for such actions we may say that in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/G$
\end_inset

 we are identifying points in the same 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-orbit with this identification process not 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

crushing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by identifying points in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that are arbitrarly close to each other.
 An example where things go horribly wrong is the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 via additive translations.
 This is a continuous action, but the quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}/\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is very bad: any two 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

-orbits in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 contain arbitrarily close points! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Here are some examples of free and properly discontinuous actions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The antipodal map on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},\dots,a_{n+1})\mapsto(-a_{1},\dots,-a_{n+1})$
\end_inset

, viewed as an action of the integers mod 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 is free and properly discontinuous: freeness is clear, as is continuity,
 and for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S^{n}$
\end_inset

 the points near 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 all have their antipodes far away! 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $X:=\mathbf{V}(x^{3}+y^{3}+z^{3}-1)\subseteq\mathbb{C}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the action 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},a_{2},a_{3})\mapsto(\zeta_{3}a_{1},\zeta_{3}a_{2},\zeta_{3})$
\end_inset

, viewed as an action of the integers mod 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 is free and properly discontinuous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=S^{1}\times S^{1}$
\end_inset

 be a product of two circles, where the circle 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S^{1}=\{z\in\mathbb{C}\mid|z|=1\}
\]

\end_inset

is viewed as a topological group (using multiplication in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, so both the group law and inversion 
\begin_inset Formula $z\mapsto1/z=\overline{z}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 are continuous).
 The visibly continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $(z,w)\mapsto(1/z,-w)=(\overline{z},-w)$
\end_inset

 reflects through the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis in the first circle and rotates 
\begin_inset Formula $180$
\end_inset

-degree in the second circle, and it is its own inverse.
 Thus, this give an action by the order-
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 of integers mod 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 The associated quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $X/G$
\end_inset

 will be called the (set-theoretic) 
\series bold
Klein bottle
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a locally Hausdorff topological space with a free and properly discontinuous
 action by a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 There is a unique topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X/G$
\end_inset

 such that the quotient map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:X\to X/G$
\end_inset

 is a continuous map that is a local homeomorphism (i.e.
 each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 admits a neighborhood mapping homeomorphically onto an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X/G$
\end_inset

).
 Moreover, the quotient map is open.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $S\subseteq X/G$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if its preimage in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is open, and if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is an open set that is disjoint from 
\begin_inset Formula $U.g$
\end_inset

 for all nontrivial 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 then the map 
\begin_inset Formula $U\to X/G$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism onto its open image 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{U}$
\end_inset

 and the natural map 
\begin_inset Formula $U\times G\to\pi^{-1}(\overline{U})$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{U}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,g)\mapsto u.g$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism when 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is given the discrete topology.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The topology in this theorem is called the 
\series bold
quotient topology
\series default
, and it is locally Hausdorff since 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to X/G$
\end_inset

 is a local homeomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Sketch: we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is an open map.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and pick 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}.g\cap U_{x}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G\backslash\{1\}$
\end_inset

.
 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U_{x})$
\end_inset

 is open.
 The inverse image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U_{x})$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is a disjoint union of open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{g\in G}U_{x}.g$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U_{x})$
\end_inset

 is open.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be any open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, choose 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}.g\cap U_{x}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G\backslash\{1\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}\subset U$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(U)=\pi\left(\bigcup_{x\in U}U_{x}\right)=\bigcup_{x\in U}\pi(U_{x})
\]

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U)$
\end_inset

 is open.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Möbius Strip) Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(-a,a)\times S^{1}$
\end_inset

, and let the group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 act on it with the non-trivial element acting by 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,w)\mapsto(-t,-w)$
\end_inset

.
 This is easily checked to be a continuous action for the discrete topology
 of the group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, and it is free and properly discontinuous.
 The quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
Möbius strip 
\series default
of height 
\begin_inset Formula $2a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To check that the Möbius strip 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{a}$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff, we use the quotient criterion: the set of points in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

 with the form 
\begin_inset Formula $((t,w),(t',w'))$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $(t',w')=(t,w)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $(t',w')=(-t,-w)$
\end_inset

 is checked to be closed by using the sequential criterion in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

: suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(t_{n},w_{n})\sim(t'_{n},w'_{n})$
\end_inset

 are sequences in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

 which converge 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,w)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(t',w')$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Then we need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,w)\sim(t',w')$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,w)\neq(t',w')$
\end_inset

.
 Choose open neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,w)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U'$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(t',w')$
\end_inset

 respectively such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U'=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and such that eventually 
\begin_inset Formula $(t_{n},w_{n})\neq(t_{n}',w_{n}')$
\end_inset

 (We can do this because they converge to different limits and our space
 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff).
 Thus, eventually we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(t_{n}',w_{n}')=(-t_{n},-w_{n})\to(-t,-w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Product Topology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 be a set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X_{\lambda},\tau_{\lambda})$
\end_inset

 be a topological space for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

, we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\lambda}\colon\prod_{\lambda}X_{\lambda}\to X_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 to be the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

th 
\series bold
projection map 
\series default
defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{\lambda}((x_{\lambda}))=x_{\lambda}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{\lambda})\in\prod_{\lambda}X_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 We define the 
\series bold
product topology
\series default
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{\lambda}X_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{\lambda}\tau_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

, to be the topology generated by sets of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{\pi_{\lambda}^{-1}(U_{\lambda})\mid\lambda\in\Lambda\text{ and }U_{\lambda}\in\tau_{\lambda}\}.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, the product is the 
\emph on
weakest 
\emph default
topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{\lambda}X_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 which makes all of the projection maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 continuous.
 Recall that the topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 generated by a subcollection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}\subseteq\mathcal{P}(X)$
\end_inset

 is obtained by adjoining 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

 to the entire collection as well as all adjoint all arbitrary unions of
 finite intersections of members of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 to the entire collection.
 Note that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\mu}\in\tau_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{\mu}^{-1}(U_{\mu})=U_{\mu}\times\prod_{\lambda\in\Lambda\backslash\{\mu\}}X_{\lambda},
\]

\end_inset

and for each distinct 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu,\kappa\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\mu}\in\tau_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\kappa}\in\tau_{\kappa}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi_{\mu}^{-1}(U_{\mu})\cap\pi_{\kappa}^{-1}(U_{\kappa}) & =U_{\mu}\times U_{\kappa}\times\prod_{\lambda\in\Lambda\backslash\{\mu,\kappa\}}X_{\lambda}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In general, a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{\lambda}\tau_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 consists of sets of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\prod_{\lambda_{0}\in\Lambda_{0}}U_{\lambda_{0}}\times\prod_{\lambda\in\Lambda\backslash\Lambda_{0}}X_{\lambda},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a finite subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\lambda_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\lambda_{0}}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}\in\Lambda_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 be a set, let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X_{\lambda},\tau_{\lambda})$
\end_inset

 be a topological space for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be a topological space, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to\prod_{\lambda}X_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 be a function.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\lambda}\circ f\colon Y\to X_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is continuous for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continous, then each 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\lambda}\circ f$
\end_inset

 is a composition of continuous functions and is hence continuous.
 Conversely, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\lambda}\circ f$
\end_inset

 is continuous for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 To show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continous, it suffices to show that the premiage of a subbase element
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\lambda}^{-1}(U_{\lambda})$
\end_inset

 is open.
 But note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f^{-1}(\pi_{\lambda}^{-1}(U_{\lambda})) & =(\pi_{\lambda}\circ f)^{-1}(U_{\lambda})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

is open since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\lambda}\circ f$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Coproduct Topology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 be a set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X_{\lambda},\tau_{\lambda})$
\end_inset

 be a topological space for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

, we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\lambda}\colon\prod_{\lambda}X_{\lambda}\to X_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 to be the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

th 
\series bold
projection map 
\series default
defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{\lambda}((x_{\lambda}))=x_{\lambda}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{\lambda})\in\prod_{\lambda}X_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 We define the 
\series bold
product topology
\series default
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{\lambda}X_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{\lambda}\tau_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

, to be the topology generated by sets of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{\pi_{\lambda}^{-1}(U_{\lambda})\mid\lambda\in\Lambda\text{ and }U_{\lambda}\in\tau_{\lambda}\}.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, the product is the 
\emph on
weakest 
\emph default
topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{\lambda}X_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 which makes all of the projection maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 continuous.
 Recall that the topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 generated by a subcollection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}\subseteq\mathcal{P}(X)$
\end_inset

 is obtained by adjoining 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

 to the entire collection as well as all adjoint all arbitrary unions of
 finite intersections of members of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 to the entire collection.
 Note that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\mu}\in\tau_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{\mu}^{-1}(U_{\mu})=U_{\mu}\times\prod_{\lambda\in\Lambda\backslash\{\mu\}}X_{\lambda},
\]

\end_inset

and for each distinct 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu,\kappa\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\mu}\in\tau_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\kappa}\in\tau_{\kappa}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi_{\mu}^{-1}(U_{\mu})\cap\pi_{\kappa}^{-1}(U_{\kappa}) & =U_{\mu}\times U_{\kappa}\times\prod_{\lambda\in\Lambda\backslash\{\mu,\kappa\}}X_{\lambda}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In general, a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{\lambda}\tau_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 consists of sets of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\prod_{\lambda_{0}\in\Lambda_{0}}U_{\lambda_{0}}\times\prod_{\lambda\in\Lambda\backslash\Lambda_{0}}X_{\lambda},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a finite subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\lambda_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\lambda_{0}}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}\in\Lambda_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 be a set, let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X_{\lambda},\tau_{\lambda})$
\end_inset

 be a topological space for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be a topological space, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to\prod_{\lambda}X_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 be a function.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\lambda}\circ f\colon Y\to X_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is continuous for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continous, then each 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\lambda}\circ f$
\end_inset

